FLASHCARDS.push(

  // h8-01 The English Civil War
  {id:"h8fc-01-A",islandId:"h8-01",
   front:"What were the main causes of the English Civil War?",
   back:"The main causes included:\n\n1. Religion — Charles I imposed Anglican practices on Scotland, provoking the Bishops' Wars.\n2. Money — Charles raised taxes (e.g. Ship Money) without Parliament's consent.\n3. Divine Right — Charles I believed he ruled by God's authority and did not need Parliament.\n4. Personal Rule — from 1629 to 1640, Charles ruled without Parliament (the 'Eleven Years' Tyranny').\n5. The Grand Remonstrance (1641) — Parliament listed its grievances, deepening the rift.\n\nWar broke out in 1642 when Charles raised his standard at Nottingham.",
   difficulty:2,category:"cause"},

  {id:"h8fc-01-B",islandId:"h8-01",
   front:"Who were the Cavaliers and who were the Roundheads?",
   back:"Cavaliers (Royalists): supporters of King Charles I. Often aristocrats, Catholics and Church of England supporters. Their nickname came from the Spanish 'caballero' (horseman) and was used mockingly by their opponents.\n\nRoundheads (Parliamentarians): supporters of Parliament. Included many Puritans, merchants and tradespeople. Their nickname referred to the short haircuts worn by some Parliamentary soldiers.\n\nNot everyone chose a side — many ordinary people tried to avoid the conflict altogether.",
   difficulty:1,category:"fact"},

  {id:"h8fc-01-C",islandId:"h8-01",
   front:"What were the key battles of the English Civil War and why did they matter?",
   back:"Battle of Edgehill (1642) — the first major battle; inconclusive, but showed Parliament could resist the king.\n\nBattle of Marston Moor (1644) — decisive Parliamentarian victory; gave Parliament control of northern England. Oliver Cromwell's cavalry (the 'Ironsides') proved vital.\n\nBattle of Naseby (1645) — the turning point. Cromwell's New Model Army crushed the Royalist forces. Charles I's private letters were captured, revealing he had sought foreign help.\n\nAfter Naseby, the Royalist cause collapsed. Charles surrendered to the Scots in 1646.",
   difficulty:2,category:"fact"},

  {id:"h8fc-01-D",islandId:"h8-01",
   front:"Why was the execution of Charles I in 1649 so significant?",
   back:"On 30 January 1649, Charles I was beheaded outside the Banqueting House in London — the first time an English monarch had been publicly tried and executed.\n\nSignificance:\n• It was a direct challenge to the idea of the Divine Right of Kings.\n• It shocked Europe — monarchs everywhere feared it set a dangerous precedent.\n• It led to the abolition of the monarchy and the House of Lords.\n• England became a Commonwealth (republic) under Parliament, then a Protectorate under Cromwell.\n• The execution demonstrated that rulers could be held accountable by law.",
   difficulty:2,category:"significance"},

  {id:"h8fc-01-E",islandId:"h8-01",
   front:"What was Oliver Cromwell's role as Lord Protector and what was life like under the Protectorate?",
   back:"Oliver Cromwell became Lord Protector of the Commonwealth in 1653 — effectively ruling as a military dictator, though he refused the crown when offered.\n\nLife under the Protectorate:\n• Strict Puritan laws — theatres, gambling and some sports were banned.\n• Christmas celebrations were restricted.\n• Ireland and Scotland were brought under English control by military force; Cromwell's campaign in Ireland (1649–50) caused huge civilian deaths.\n• Cromwell dismissed Parliament twice when it challenged him.\n\nAfter his death in 1658, his son Richard briefly ruled but resigned, paving the way for the Restoration of the monarchy in 1660.",
   difficulty:3,category:"consequence"},

  // h8-02 The Restoration & Glorious Revolution
  {id:"h8fc-02-A",islandId:"h8-02",
   front:"How and why was the monarchy restored in 1660?",
   back:"After Cromwell's death (1658) and his son Richard's brief rule, the country grew tired of military government. General George Monck marched his army to London and negotiated the return of Charles II.\n\nCharles signed the Declaration of Breda (1660), promising:\n• A general pardon for most people who had opposed the Crown.\n• Religious toleration.\n• To work with Parliament on key decisions.\n\nCharles II entered London on 29 May 1660 to great public celebrations. The date became known as Oak Apple Day (Royal Oak Day).",
   difficulty:2,category:"cause"},

  {id:"h8fc-02-B",islandId:"h8-02",
   front:"What were the Great Plague and the Great Fire of London?",
   back:"Great Plague of 1665:\n• Bubonic plague killed approximately 100,000 people in London — about a quarter of the city's population.\n• Spread by fleas on rats; people fled the city; 'plague pits' were dug for mass burials.\n• Marked by red crosses on doors of infected houses.\n\nGreat Fire of London (2–6 September 1666):\n• Started in a bakery on Pudding Lane; spread rapidly through timber-framed buildings.\n• Destroyed around 13,000 houses and 87 churches, including St Paul's Cathedral.\n• King Charles II personally directed fire-fighting efforts.\n• Accidentally helped end the plague by destroying the rat-infested slums.\n• London was rebuilt in brick and stone, with the new St Paul's designed by Christopher Wren.",
   difficulty:1,category:"fact"},

  {id:"h8fc-02-C",islandId:"h8-02",
   front:"What caused the Glorious Revolution of 1688?",
   back:"James II became king in 1685 and alarmed Protestant England by:\n• Appointing Catholics to senior positions in the army and government.\n• Issuing the Declaration of Indulgence (1687), granting religious freedom without Parliament's consent.\n• Having a Catholic son (June 1688), meaning a Catholic dynasty seemed permanent.\n\nIn November 1688, the Protestant William of Orange (James's son-in-law) was invited by leading nobles to invade.\n\nJames II fled to France — it was called 'Glorious' because it was bloodless in England (though not in Ireland or Scotland). William and his wife Mary (James II's Protestant daughter) became joint monarchs.",
   difficulty:2,category:"cause"},

  {id:"h8fc-02-D",islandId:"h8-02",
   front:"What was the Bill of Rights (1689) and why was it important?",
   back:"The Bill of Rights (1689) set out the limits of royal power and the rights of Parliament. Key provisions:\n\n• The monarch could not suspend laws or raise taxes without Parliament's consent.\n• Free elections for Members of Parliament must be held.\n• Freedom of speech in Parliament was guaranteed.\n• A standing army could not be kept in peacetime without Parliament's approval.\n• Excessive bail and cruel punishments were prohibited.\n\nSignificance: It established constitutional monarchy in Britain — the principle that the monarch rules under the law, not above it. This principle influenced later democratic systems, including the US Constitution.",
   difficulty:2,category:"significance"},

  {id:"h8fc-02-E",islandId:"h8-02",
   front:"What is constitutional monarchy and how did Britain arrive at it?",
   back:"A constitutional monarchy is a system where the monarch is head of state but their powers are limited by law and Parliament.\n\nBritain arrived at this through a series of events:\n1. Magna Carta (1215) — first limits on royal power.\n2. English Civil War (1642–51) — Parliament challenged and defeated the king.\n3. Execution of Charles I (1649) — showed monarchs were accountable.\n4. Restoration (1660) — monarchy returned, but with more reliance on Parliament.\n5. Glorious Revolution (1688) — Parliament chose who should be king.\n6. Bill of Rights (1689) — formally set down Parliament's supremacy over the Crown.\n\nThis gradual process made Britain a model of constitutional government.",
   difficulty:3,category:"concept"},

  // h8-03 The British Empire
  {id:"h8fc-03-A",islandId:"h8-03",
   front:"How did the British Empire grow from the 17th to the 19th century?",
   back:"The British Empire expanded in stages:\n\n17th century: Early colonies in North America (e.g. Virginia, 1607) and the Caribbean; the East India Company established trade posts in India.\n\n18th century: Victories in the Seven Years' War (1756–63) gave Britain Canada and parts of India; Australia claimed after Cook's voyages (1770); slave trade at its peak.\n\n19th century: Scramble for Africa (1880s–90s) — Britain seized large parts of Africa; India became the 'jewel in the crown'; the empire covered roughly a quarter of the world's land and a quarter of its population by 1900.\n\nMotivations: trade, raw materials, strategic advantage, missionary activity and belief in cultural 'superiority'.",
   difficulty:2,category:"fact"},

  {id:"h8fc-03-B",islandId:"h8-03",
   front:"What was the East India Company and how did Britain come to control India?",
   back:"The East India Company (EIC) was a trading company founded in 1600, granted a royal charter to trade with Asia. It grew to become one of the most powerful commercial organisations in history.\n\nKey stages in British control of India:\n• The EIC established trading posts (factories) and built armies of Indian soldiers (sepoys).\n• Battle of Plassey (1757): Robert Clive defeated the Nawab of Bengal, giving Britain effective control of Bengal.\n• After the Indian Uprising (Indian Mutiny) of 1857, the British Crown took direct control from the EIC.\n• Queen Victoria was declared Empress of India in 1877.\n\nBritain exploited India's resources — cotton, tea, spices — while often undermining local industries.",
   difficulty:2,category:"fact"},

  {id:"h8fc-03-C",islandId:"h8-03",
   front:"What was the impact of British colonisation on indigenous peoples?",
   back:"The impact varied but often included significant harm:\n\nAustralia: Aboriginal Australians lost their land through the legal fiction of 'terra nullius' (empty land). Many were killed in frontier violence; children were later forcibly removed from families (the 'Stolen Generations').\n\nAfrica: The Scramble for Africa (1884–85 Berlin Conference) divided the continent with no regard for existing peoples, languages or communities, causing long-lasting political divisions.\n\nIndia: Economic exploitation impoverished millions; the 1943 Bengal Famine (killing 2–3 million people) has been linked to wartime imperial policies.\n\nCultural impact: Local languages, religions and customs were suppressed; missionary education imposed British values.\n\nResistance was common — from the Indian Uprising (1857) to the Zulu Wars (1879).",
   difficulty:3,category:"consequence"},

  {id:"h8fc-03-D",islandId:"h8-03",
   front:"What were the economic motives behind British colonisation?",
   back:"Britain's empire was driven heavily by economic interests:\n\n• Raw materials: colonies supplied cotton (India), rubber (Malaya), gold and diamonds (South Africa), sugar (Caribbean).\n• Markets: colonies were forced or encouraged to buy British manufactured goods, boosting British industry.\n• Trade routes: strategic ports (e.g. Gibraltar, Cape Town, Singapore) controlled global shipping lanes.\n• The Slave Trade: before abolition, Britain transported approximately 3 million enslaved Africans to the Caribbean and Americas, generating enormous profits for British merchants and plantation owners.\n• Investment: British banks and companies invested heavily in colonial infrastructure (railways, ports), but profits largely flowed back to Britain.\n\nCritics argue the empire enriched Britain while keeping colonies poor — a process historians call 'economic drain'.",
   difficulty:2,category:"cause"},

  {id:"h8fc-03-E",islandId:"h8-03",
   front:"What are the key arguments in the modern debate about the legacy of the British Empire?",
   back:"The legacy of empire is actively debated in Britain today:\n\nArguments that emphasise harm:\n• Slavery, exploitation and violence caused immense suffering.\n• Economic 'drain' impoverished colonies for generations.\n• Arbitrary borders drawn by colonial powers caused ongoing conflicts.\n• Indigenous cultures and peoples were damaged or destroyed.\n\nArguments that emphasise other legacies:\n• Infrastructure (railways, ports) was built in some colonies.\n• Common legal and parliamentary systems were introduced.\n• The end of the slave trade (1807) was led by Britain.\n\nHistorians and communities in former colonies generally view the empire more critically than many in Britain. The debate shapes discussions about statues, school curricula and reparations today.\n\nA balanced view acknowledges both the economic benefits to Britain and the serious harm caused to colonised peoples.",
   difficulty:3,category:"significance"},

  // h8-04 The Industrial Revolution
  {id:"h8fc-04-A",islandId:"h8-04",
   front:"What were the main causes of the Industrial Revolution in Britain?",
   back:"Britain was the first country to industrialise (c.1760–1840) for several reasons:\n\n• Agricultural Revolution — enclosures freed up a labour force for factories.\n• Natural resources — coal and iron ore were plentiful.\n• Colonial trade — empire provided raw materials and markets.\n• Capital — merchants had profits to invest in new machinery.\n• Stable government — Parliament protected property rights and encouraged trade.\n• Geography — rivers and coastline made transport easier.\n• Inventors and entrepreneurs — James Watt, Josiah Wedgwood, Richard Arkwright drove innovation.\n\nThese factors combined to make Britain uniquely ready for rapid industrialisation.",
   difficulty:2,category:"cause"},

  {id:"h8fc-04-B",islandId:"h8-04",
   front:"What were the key inventions of the Industrial Revolution?",
   back:"Key inventions transformed British industry:\n\n• Spinning Jenny (James Hargreaves, 1764) — spun multiple threads at once, revolutionising textile production.\n• Water Frame (Richard Arkwright, 1769) — used water power to spin cotton, enabling large factories.\n• Steam Engine (James Watt, improved 1769) — provided reliable power for factories, mines and transport.\n• Power Loom (Edmund Cartwright, 1785) — mechanised weaving.\n• Stephenson's Rocket (1829) — demonstrated the viability of steam-powered railways.\n• Bessemer Converter (Henry Bessemer, 1856) — made mass production of steel possible.\n\nThese inventions created the factory system and moved production from homes and workshops to large industrial buildings.",
   difficulty:1,category:"fact"},

  {id:"h8fc-04-C",islandId:"h8-04",
   front:"What were working conditions like in factories and mines during the Industrial Revolution?",
   back:"Working conditions were often dangerous and exploitative:\n\nFactories:\n• 12–16 hour working days; six days a week.\n• Dangerous machinery with no safety guards.\n• Children as young as five worked as 'scavengers', picking up loose cotton under moving machinery.\n• Fines for lateness, talking or opening windows.\n\nCoal Mines:\n• Children worked as 'trappers' (opening ventilation doors in the dark) and 'hurriers' (pushing coal carts).\n• Constant risk of roof collapse, flooding and gas explosions.\n• The Mines Act (1842) banned women and children under ten from working underground.\n\nFactory Acts (from 1833) gradually limited working hours for children, though enforcement was weak initially.",
   difficulty:2,category:"consequence"},

  {id:"h8fc-04-D",islandId:"h8-04",
   front:"How did urbanisation change Britain during the Industrial Revolution?",
   back:"Before industrialisation, most people lived in rural areas. By 1851, more than half of Britain's population lived in towns and cities — the first country in the world to achieve this.\n\nEffects of urbanisation:\n• Cities like Manchester, Birmingham and Leeds grew rapidly and chaotically.\n• Housing was overcrowded, poorly built and had no running water or sewerage.\n• Disease spread easily — cholera epidemics (1831, 1848, 1854) killed thousands.\n• Air and water pollution from factories made cities unhealthy.\n• Social problems: crime, poverty, alcoholism increased in slum areas.\n• But also: growth of middle class, new leisure activities, public parks and libraries later in the century.\n\nMany historians call this the 'dark side' of industrial progress.",
   difficulty:2,category:"consequence"},

  {id:"h8fc-04-E",islandId:"h8-04",
   front:"How did the transport revolution transform Britain?",
   back:"The transport revolution had several phases:\n\nCanals (from 1760s): Cheap, slow transport for heavy goods like coal and pottery. The Duke of Bridgewater's Canal (1761) cut the price of coal in Manchester by half. By 1815, over 2,000 miles of canals criss-crossed England.\n\nRailways (from 1830s): George Stephenson's Stockton to Darlington Railway (1825) was the first public steam railway; the Liverpool to Manchester Railway (1830) opened railway travel to passengers.\n• By 1850, over 6,000 miles of track had been laid.\n• Railways transformed the economy: goods moved faster, prices fell, national markets developed.\n• 'Railway mania' in the 1840s saw enormous investment in new lines.\n\nRoads: John Macadam developed a new road surface (tarmacadam), making coach travel faster and more reliable.",
   difficulty:2,category:"fact"},

  // h8-05 Social Reform & the Victorians
  {id:"h8fc-05-A",islandId:"h8-05",
   front:"What was Victorian society like and how was it divided by class?",
   back:"Victorian society (1837–1901) was rigidly divided into social classes:\n\nUpper class: aristocracy and landed gentry; inherited wealth and land; political power through the House of Lords.\n\nMiddle class (growing rapidly): factory owners, merchants, lawyers, doctors; believed in hard work, thrift and respectability; lived in suburban villas.\n\nWorking class (majority): factory and mine workers, servants, agricultural labourers; lived in cramped terraced housing; little political power until later reforms.\n\nWomen had very limited rights regardless of class — married women could not own property until the Married Women's Property Act (1882).\n\nVictorian values emphasised duty, religion, respectability and 'self-help' (Samuel Smiles's 1859 book popularised this idea).",
   difficulty:1,category:"fact"},

  {id:"h8fc-05-B",islandId:"h8-05",
   front:"What were the public health problems of Victorian Britain and how were they addressed?",
   back:"Victorian cities faced severe public health crises:\n\nProblems:\n• Cholera epidemics (1831, 1848, 1854) — spread through contaminated water.\n• Typhoid, tuberculosis and typhus were widespread in slums.\n• No sewerage system — sewage flowed into rivers, including the Thames.\n• The 'Great Stink' of 1858 — the Thames smelled so badly that Parliament had to close.\n\nReforms:\n• John Snow (1854) — proved cholera was waterborne by mapping cases in Soho; removed the Broad Street pump handle.\n• Joseph Bazalgette built London's sewer system (1858–75), dramatically reducing disease.\n• Public Health Acts (1848, 1875) — required local councils to improve sanitation.\n• The death rate in London fell significantly by the 1880s.",
   difficulty:2,category:"consequence"},

  {id:"h8fc-05-C",islandId:"h8-05",
   front:"Who was Lord Shaftesbury and what did he achieve?",
   back:"Anthony Ashley Cooper, 7th Earl of Shaftesbury (1801–1885), was one of the most important social reformers of the Victorian era.\n\nAchievements:\n• Factory Act (1833) — though passed before Shaftesbury's key campaigns, he built on it: children under nine banned from textile factories; inspectors appointed.\n• Mines Act (1842) — he championed this law, banning women and children under ten from underground mining.\n• Ten Hours Act (1847) — limited working hours for women and children to ten hours a day in textile factories.\n• Lunacy Act (1845) — improved conditions in mental asylums.\n• Ragged Schools: supported free education for the poorest children.\n\nShaftesbury's work showed that Parliament could intervene to protect vulnerable people — a shift away from laissez-faire attitudes.",
   difficulty:2,category:"significance"},

  {id:"h8fc-05-D",islandId:"h8-05",
   front:"What was Florence Nightingale's contribution to healthcare reform?",
   back:"Florence Nightingale (1820–1910) transformed nursing and hospital care.\n\nCrimean War (1854–56):\n• Nightingale led a team of nurses to Scutari (modern-day Istanbul) military hospital.\n• She found appalling conditions — soldiers dying from infections, not just wounds.\n• By improving sanitation, ventilation and nutrition, she dramatically reduced the death rate from 42% to around 2%.\n\nStatistical innovation:\n• Nightingale used pioneering statistical diagrams (her 'rose diagrams') to prove that most deaths were preventable.\n• Her use of data to drive reform was revolutionary.\n\nLegacy:\n• Founded the Nightingale Training School for Nurses (1860) at St Thomas's Hospital, London.\n• Her book Notes on Nursing (1859) became a standard text.\n• She transformed nursing from a low-status job into a respected profession.",
   difficulty:2,category:"significance"},

  {id:"h8fc-05-E",islandId:"h8-05",
   front:"What was the workhouse system and how was Victorian education reformed?",
   back:"The Workhouse System:\n• The Poor Law Amendment Act (1834) created a system of workhouses — institutions where the destitute could receive food and shelter in exchange for hard labour.\n• Conditions were deliberately harsh (the 'less eligibility' principle) to deter people from relying on state help.\n• Families were separated; diets were minimal; work was degrading (oakum picking, stone breaking).\n• Charles Dickens's Oliver Twist (1837) famously exposed workhouse conditions.\n\nEducation Reform:\n• Before 1870, schooling was provided mainly by churches and charities.\n• Forster's Education Act (1870) — created Board Schools in areas with no existing provision; the first step towards universal education.\n• Education Act (1880) — made school attendance compulsory for children aged 5–10.\n• Education Act (1891) — made elementary education free.",
   difficulty:2,category:"fact"}

);

